  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Return Run with Walking Breaks\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 3-minute brisk walk to warm up the foot and ankle. Focus on relaxed breathing and gentle foot strike. Stop immediately if you feel any sharp pain in the right foot.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First easy running segment. Keep effort conversational — you should be able to speak in full sentences. Land softly, avoid overstriding. Monitor right foot closely.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk break. This is intentional and important — not a sign of weakness. Use this to check in with your foot. Rate any discomfort on a 0-10 scale mentally.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second easy running segment. Same easy effort as before. If foot discomfort is above a 3/10, switch to walking for the remainder of the session.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second walk break. Stay relaxed. Shake out the legs gently.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final running segment. Keep it easy and controlled. Finishing feeling like you could do more is the goal today.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Finish with a 2-minute easy walk. Gentle calf and foot stretches after — no aggressive stretching of the plantar fascia.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with a 3-minute brisk walk before any running. This helps warm up the plantar fascia and surrounding tissues gradually. If the foot feels stiff or sore during the walk, extend the walk warm-up and reduce the running segments accordingly.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 2 minutes after your final running segment. Follow with gentle standing calf raises (not aggressive stretching) and a seated towel stretch for the foot if your physio has cleared these. Ice the foot for 10-15 minutes if there is any residual soreness.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Welcome back, James. This first session of the week is built around your physio clearance — 20 minutes easy with walking breaks as needed. Your pre-injury VDOT of 46.5 tells us your aerobic engine is strong, but right now the priority is tissue tolerance, not fitness. The run-walk structure here is deliberate: it lets the plantar fascia load and recover in short cycles, which is actually how connective tissue adapts best. Easy pace today is the slower end of your easy range (around 5:58/km) — there is no benefit to pushing faster while returning from injury. The goal of this session is simply to finish feeling good and gather information about how your foot responds.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Easy Run — Foot Check-In\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute walk warm-up. Pay attention to how the foot feels compared to Tuesday. Morning stiffness that eases within the first few minutes is normal; pain that worsens is a signal to stop.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First running segment — slightly longer than Tuesday if Tuesday went well. If Tuesday caused any lingering soreness, keep this at 4 minutes and add an extra walk break instead.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk break. Check in with the foot. Any discomfort above 3/10 means you walk the rest of the session — and that is still a successful workout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second running segment. Maintain easy conversational effort. Focus on relaxed shoulders and a light foot strike rather than pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk cooldown. Gentle calf stretches. Note how the foot feels for your post-run log.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3-minute walk before running. If the foot is noticeably more sore than it was before Tuesday's run, consider replacing this session with a 20-minute easy walk instead — that still counts as active recovery and keeps the week on track.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2-minute walk cooldown followed by gentle calf stretches. Ice if needed. Log your foot soreness rating (0-10) after this session — this information will help guide next week's progression.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This midweek session builds gently on Tuesday. The run segments are slightly longer, but the total time stays within your 20-minute clearance. The key question this session answers is: how does the foot respond to a second run in the same week? That information is genuinely valuable — it tells us whether the tissue is adapting or needs more time. There is no speed work here, no pace targets beyond easy effort, and no pressure to hit a distance number. Your recent training history shows you have been building carefully (2.5km, 8.9km, 6.4km over the past three weeks), and this plan respects that trajectory.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Saturday Long Run — Easy and Exploratory\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk warm-up. Saturday is your designated long run day, but during return-to-run, 'long' simply means the week's most intentional session — not necessarily the most distance. Start with a full 3-minute walk.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First running segment. Easy effort, slow end of the easy pace range. This is the longest single running block of the week — only attempt it if Tuesday and Thursday went well.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk break. Intentional recovery. Use this to assess cumulative fatigue from the week.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second running segment. Same easy effort. If the foot is speaking up at all, walk the remainder — you will have still completed a meaningful session.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final walk break before cooldown.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute walk cooldown. Take your time. This is the end of your training week — finishing well matters more than finishing fast.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Full 3-minute walk warm-up before any running. Saturday's session should only happen if you are not carrying significant foot soreness from earlier in the week. If Tuesday or Thursday left the foot sore for more than a few hours afterward, replace this session with a 20-minute easy walk and check in with your physio before next week.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3-minute walk cooldown. Gentle calf and foot care afterward — whatever your physio has recommended. Ice if there is any soreness. Take note of how the foot feels in the 24 hours after this session, as that is often the most informative window for plantar fasciitis response.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your long run slot, James — and even at 20 minutes it counts. The physiological purpose of a long run is time on feet and aerobic stimulus, both of which you are getting here. The run-walk structure means the plantar fascia gets loaded progressively rather than continuously, which is actually a smarter approach right now than grinding through a continuous run. Your weekly volume across these three sessions sits around 10km, which aligns well with your recent training history and keeps progression conservative. The most important thing this week is not the distance — it is finishing all three sessions with foot soreness that stays below a 3/10 and resolves within a few hours. That is the green light for next week. How does this plan feel to you as a starting point?\",\"perceived_effort\":4}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
